# 1. Distribution of each numerical column
for column in data.columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    sns.histplot(data[column], kde=True, bins=30, color="blue")
    plt.title(f"Distribution of {column}", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel(column, fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel("Frequency", fontsize=12)
    plt.show()
In[]:
#Observations:

#Each histogram reveals the frequency of data points for respective columns.

#Skewness or multimodal distributions, if present, are noted.

#Potential outliers can be observed in the tails of the distribution.

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    sns.boxplot(x=data[column], color="green")
    plt.title(f"Boxplot of {column}", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel(column, fontsize=12)
    plt.show()

In[28]:
# 5. Scatter plots for relationships
for col1 in data.columns:
    for col2 in data.columns:
        if col1 != col2:
            plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
            sns.scatterplot(data=data, x=col1, y=col2, alpha=0.7, color="purple")
            plt.title(f"{col1} vs {col2}", fontsize=14)
            plt.xlabel(col1, fontsize=12)
            plt.ylabel(col2, fontsize=12)
            plt.show()
In[]:
#Observations:

#Scatter plots indicate trends, clusters, or anomalies in relationships.

#For example, increasing "Study Hours" might correlate with better "Grades," but anomalies should be noted for further exploration.

# 6. Analyzing Grades with other factors (specific insights)
sns.lmplot(data=data, x="Study Hours", y="Grades", height=6, aspect=1.5, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.6})
plt.title("Study Hours vs Grades", fontsize=14)
plt.show()

sns.lmplot(data=data, x="Attendance (%)", y="Grades", height=6, aspect=1.5, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.6})

plt.show()

plt.show()

# 7. Bar plot for categorical-style data (Attendance and Grades as an example)
import pandas as pd
data['Attendance Group'] = pd.cut(data['Attendance (%)'], bins=[0, 50, 75, 100], labels=['Low', 'Medium', 'High'])
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.barplot(data=data, x="Attendance Group", y="Grades", ci=None, palette="viridis")
plt.title("Attendance Group vs Average Grades", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Attendance Group", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Average Grades", fontsize=12)
plt.show()
